{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608871"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:37:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:37:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16048"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16048"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.04,0.12,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63689"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8662"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20901"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63689"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENeural tube formation is a critical process in early embryonic development. The neural tube gives rise to the central nervous system, including the brain and spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following gestational ages represents the lowest risk period for neural tube defects?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Week 5","Week 9","Week 12","Week 16","Week 35"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeural tube closure occurs between weeks 3-4 of embryonic development. After this critical period, the risk of neural tube defects decreases significantly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk is highest during the period of neural tube formation and closure:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeek 5\u003C/strong\u003E represents a period shortly after neural tube closure when the risk is still relatively high\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeek 9\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EWeek 12\u003C/strong\u003E are during the fetal period when the neural tube has already closed but early developmental processes are still ongoing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeek 16\u003C/strong\u003E is mid-pregnancy when basic neural development is established but continued growth occurs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeek 35\u003C/strong\u003E represents late pregnancy when neural tube formation was completed months earlier, thus carrying the lowest risk of neural tube defects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is why folic acid supplementation is crucial before conception and during early pregnancy, as it helps prevent neural tube defects during this critical period of development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neural tube closure occurs between weeks 3-4 of embryonic development","Neural tube defects occur when the neural tube fails to close properly during early embryonic development","After neural tube closure is complete, the risk of neural tube defects is minimal"],"references":["Greene ND, Copp AJ. Neural tube defects. Annu Rev Neurosci. 2014;37:221-42. doi: 10.1146/annurev-neuro-062012-170354. PMID: 25032496; PMCID: PMC4486472.","Avagliano L, Massa V, George TM, Qureshy S, Bulfamante GP, Finnell RH. Overview on neural tube defects: From development to physical characteristics. Birth Defects Res. 2019 Nov 15;111(19):1455-1467. doi: 10.1002/bdr2.1380. Epub 2018 Nov 12. PMID: 30421543; PMCID: PMC6511489.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49128"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:08:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:08:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG